observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the Management the following:
Maintain the practice of sending demand letters to employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;
Require the Municipal Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter;
For unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still failed to settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to FS on the actual status of unliquidated cash advances for confidential fund, particularly those granted prior to the effectivity of COA-DBM JC 2015-01; and
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters.

We recommended the following to management: 

11.	Municipal Budget Officer strictly comply with the PS limitation prescribed under Section 325 (a) of R.A. No. 7160 in the preparation of the annual and supplemental budgets;

12. The Municipal Mayor being the Local Chief Executive to be guided by the conditions of the agency's annual and supplemental budgets to ensure that the budgeting requirements are completely complied with;

13. The Municipal Accountant ensure that the actual expenses for one fiscal year do not exceed the required 55% PS limitation; and

14. The concerned officials exert effort in reducing its PS expenses by identifying and funding only PS items that are of priority concerns so that it can continue to allocate adequate funds for the implementation of other planned and development projects that are beneficial to its constituents.

Recommendations:
We recommended the following to management:
Municipal Budget Officer strictly comply with the PS limitation prescribed under Section 325 (a) of R.A. No. 7160 in the preparation of the annual and supplemental budgets;
The Municipal Mayor being the Local Chief Executive to be guided by the conditions of the agency’s annual and supplemental budgets to ensure that the budgeting requirements are completely complied with;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that the actual expenses for one fiscal year do not exceed the required 55% PS limitation; and
The concerned officials exert effort in reducing its PS expenses by identifying and funding only PS items that are of priority concerns so that it can continue to allocate adequate funds for the implementation of other planned and development projects that are beneficial to its constituents.

We recommended the following to management:

The LCE direct the HRMO to formulate uniform policy and procedures in engaging and managing COS and JO personnel taking into consideration the issuances of Civil Service Commission as to the appropriate forms and types of contracts and classification of personnel; and internal controls to ensure that they are performing the required task, reporting to the official station, and bases of assigning wage rates;

The Sangguniang Bayan, upon review and deliberation, institutionalize the policy and procedures in engaging and managing COS and JO personnel, as prepared by the HRMO, by legislating it into an ordinance;

Refrain from engaging Contract of Services from those who are not consultants, learning service providers or technical experts to undertake special projects or jobs within a specific period; and assigning of higher rates for those who are performing routine, clerical, administrative and other support services;

Use appropriate forms or type of contracts for those who are support services personnel and should equally assign standard wage rates; and

The HRMO to carry out a periodic orientation/reorientation for COS and JO personnel so that the basic office rules and regulations, the use of travel order and the requirement of certificate of appearance, format and preparation of quantifiable accomplishment reports, roles and responsibilities of outsourced personnel, reporting lines or supervisory authority, mode or processes of separation/termination of contract shall be clear to them.

We recommended the following:

Restore or renovate the public toilets in Building No. 2 to a condition that is comfortable and ideal for use. Proper maintenance of such must also be kept;

Assign guards, policemen or government officials at the Public Market tasked to provide security and protection. Their visibility must be continuous to deter any untoward incidents caused by trouble makers and law breakers;

Direct the stallholders to remove their products that are obstructing the market aisles and corridors and warn them that failure to do so may cause the seizure of their products by the government and the imposition of fines and penalties; and

Strictly implement all the basic policies on sanitation, security and safety, and facilities, and fully enforce restrictions prescribed in the Market Code of the Municipality in order to ensure the wellbeing of the public and protect the government properties from any detrimental incidents.

5.6 We recommended that:
a. 	The Local Chief Executive require the conduct of semestral inventory taking and submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively, for verification and review;
b. 	The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer acting as the General Services Officer prepare and maintain complete Supply Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively, conduct periodic reconciliation of their records, and update the same based on the results of the physical inventory;
c. 	The Municipal Treasurer in coordination with the Municipal Accountant examine the existence of the reported inventory accounts, prepare and submit the corresponding SSMI, as basis for the recording of the necessary adjustments by the latter; and
Make the necessary adjustment in the books to reflect the correct balances of the inventory accounts.

We recommended the following:
Comply strictly with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and JMC 2015-01 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

Require the accountable officers to liquidate the overdue cash advances. Invoke the provisions of law authorizing the withholding of salary of personnel who unjustifiably fails to settle his/her cash advances within the prescribed period;

File appropriate legal action, if warranted to those who have failed to liquidate the overdue cash advances after exhausting appropriate means including those who are no longer in government service; and

4. Request the write-off of dormant accounts following the guidelines prescribed by COA Circular No. 2016-005, if warranted.

We recommended the following:

Management conduct  dialogues  with  the delinquent stallholders  in  order  to  arrive at an agreeable payment scheme to settle their accounts;

Cause the closure of the establishments, the revocation of the lease contracts and ejection in case of failure to fully settle their accounts within the agreed period and apply the administrative and judicial actions as enumerated in Section 174 of RA 7160 in order to recover the amount due;

Impose the correct amount of penalties which is two per cent daily on unpaid rentals as prescribed in the Municipal Market Code; and

Ensure that all stallholders acquire the required business permit, otherwise they should be prohibited from operating their business.

We recommended the following:

Ensure that PCF is used for non-recurring, emergency and petty expenses only;

Refrain from paying expenses that goes beyond P1,000.00 using the PCF;

Strictly observe the basic policies and procedures prescribed in Section 48 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs on the accounting and use of the PCF; and

Procurement of goods and services must be done thru public bidding, or any of the alternative mode of procurement, in accordance with the IRR of R.A. 9184 in order to ensure the most advantageous price for the government.

